1
00:00:25,394 --> 00:00:43,332
Councilor Lemming. Councilor Malayne. Councilor Scarpelli. Present. Councilor Singh. Present. Vice President Lazaro. Present. And President Pierce. Present. Seven present, none absent. Please rise to salute the flag.

2
00:00:59,853 --> 00:01:18,382
Meeting is called to order. Announcements, accolades, remembrances, reports, and records. Paper 26086 offered by Vice President Lazaro, Councilor Lemming, and President Behrs. Resolution to commemorate the life of Leonard Glenn Gliona. Be it resolved by the Medford City Council that we offer condolences to the family and friends of Lenny Gliona,

3
00:01:18,567 --> 00:01:40,471
commemorate his life. Len was a loving husband, brother, father, grandfather, and friend, a U.S. Army veteran, a retired attorney, a candidate for Medford City Council in 2023, and an ardent follower of Medford politics for over 70 years. Len often served as a generational and ideological bridge and mentor to many newcomers to Medford politics, and his presence will be deeply missed in the chambers and in our city.

4
00:01:40,977 --> 00:02:03,286
Vice President Lazaro, and then Councilor Lemming, and then Vice President Lazaro, and then Councilor Sang, and then I'll say something, and then we'll hear from any members of the public who might like to speak about one. All right, Council Vice President Lazaro, Councilor Lemming would like you to go first. Thank you.

5
00:02:03,522 --> 00:02:30,910
Len Gleona was a very dear friend of mine. I am disappointed to not be in the chambers tonight. I wrote some things down so I wouldn't forget anything. I attended his wake and funeral last week, spoke with his family.

6
00:02:33,965 --> 00:02:59,632
I knew Len as almost a colleague, though he attended city council meetings and events at the city as though they were entertaining. He really enjoyed local politics, and he enjoyed supporting people who took local politics very seriously.

7
00:03:01,555 --> 00:03:18,346
I think that because of Len and his ability to bridge the gap between people who had done politics in Medford for a very long time and people who had maybe recently moved to the city or who had

8
00:03:18,903 --> 00:03:39,811
just started getting involved in politics because of an issue that was important to them. In my case, the cost of childcare, the wage gap, a lot of issues that young families and young women started becoming interested in.

9
00:03:43,591 --> 00:03:51,910
He bridged the gap between Old Medford and New Medford very smoothly.

10
00:03:52,552 --> 00:04:13,595
He was a bridge that was very critical for me when I started becoming involved. First time I met Len was at the State Democratic Convention in Worcester in, I think, 2017. And we sat next to each other, and he asked me right away, almost right away, when I was going to run for office. And I think he was the first person that ever asked me that.

11
00:04:14,152 --> 00:04:38,063
And I've read a statistic that says that women need to be asked seven times to run for office. So I think Len was the first one for me. And he ran Nicole Morrell's campaign the first time she ran. He was unafraid to allow Medford to entertain

12
00:04:39,059 --> 00:05:01,587
young politicians in Medford, people of color who ran for office, women who ran for office, when that was very uncommon. And he saw Medford as a place that could welcome anybody in. And I really valued that in him. We would meet for lunch, we would meet for coffee, we would meet at the boat club in Medford.

13
00:05:02,380 --> 00:05:32,232
watch my kids play and have lunch and talk about, we would do a lot of gossiping. We would talk about who was doing what in town and what direction the city was going and what we would like to see. And he was my friend. And I will really, really, really miss Len. And I thought that he was a wonderful example of the sort of person that can understand what it's like to be somebody who grew up somewhere and thought that they understood the way

14
00:05:33,397 --> 00:05:58,675
their hometown was and yet could welcome in a new way of being and celebrate it and not let go necessarily of the way that he grew up, but expand his willingness to see a place for all its potential. So,

15
00:05:59,738 --> 00:06:25,608
I will really miss Len. I think the chambers will really miss Len's presence. He used to sit over on the side at the table and just watch what we were doing and celebrate everything Medford could be. So I express all of my condolences to his family. I'm so grateful to know them and I'm very sad to say goodbye to Len.

16
00:06:28,831 --> 00:06:46,499
Thank you, Vice President Zaro. Councilor Lemming. Thank you. I think I remember the first time that I ever saw Len, talked with him was sometime in 2021. It was in a backyard.

17
00:06:47,039 --> 00:07:16,452
a kickoff party where a couple of the progressive city council candidates were doing a fundraiser. I didn't know anything about anything back then, but he was sort of near the entrance. He just started talking about the mayoral elections at the time. He was talking about which city councilors he thought would make it. You could just tell the guy loved following it. He just absolutely enjoyed the scene. He enjoyed talking to people.

18
00:07:16,638 --> 00:07:38,137
I don't think it's any secret that there's generational, political, ideological gaps in the city. If you were to ask me on any day, who is the bridge between these different communities in Medford?

19
00:07:38,963 --> 00:08:07,803
The only person that I would have been able to say is that bridge is Len. And I'm not just saying that because there's a resolution now. This is a question that has come up before. And a lot of people will say, I want to bridge the gaps in the city. I want to make friends with different sides. The only person, literally, who I could think of that actually did that in practice was Len. I mean, the guy followed.

20
00:08:08,275 --> 00:08:36,473
Medford politics for over 70 years, and he was nice to everybody. And often he would support candidates that his friends that he'd known for a very long time initially wouldn't want him to support, and he would get some flack from that. But he loved talking to people, he loved talking to new candidates, and everybody respected him for it. So this is a real loss.

21
00:08:36,727 --> 00:08:48,910
I definitely remember how, when I first got involved in local politics, how there were people who were

22
00:08:49,282 --> 00:09:16,535
willing to talk to you beforehand, but most everybody's willing to talk to you if you're not involved in anything, but then suddenly you get involved and you say, these are what my politics are, this is what I believe in, and suddenly a lot of people will just completely flip on you. They'll engage with you totally differently, and it's a weird thing to deal with mentally. You also remember the people like Len who

23
00:09:16,822 --> 00:09:45,695
they just treat you the same no matter what. Like they don't let politics get in the way of who you are personally. And that's a quality that I treasure in any human being. So thank you, thank you so much. Medford's lost a real important bridge in our community. And Councilor LeMing, Councilor Sang,

24
00:09:47,652 --> 00:10:09,792
Thank you to the counselors who sponsored this and to the council. I know all the nice words that are going to be said that really deserve to be said. Glenn was someone who was like a mentor to me. He was one of the first people I met on my very first campaign.

25
00:10:10,265 --> 00:10:39,695
And as a young Asian guy getting into politics here, it often felt daunting to speak to folks who you weren't super familiar with, who you weren't sure about what they would say to you. And the first feeling I got from talking to Len was that this guy really loves Medford, and he really, really wants to see all of us involved in making it a better city.

26
00:10:40,336 --> 00:11:08,078
He was nothing but encouraging and nothing but loving to all of us and to the residents of the city, even those who he only knew a day or he didn't know at all. He was someone who, I mean, I think councilors have said this already, but who really was the bridge. He was someone who felt comfortable walking into any room,

27
00:11:08,551 --> 00:11:38,487
was loved walking into any room that everyone would be excited about seeing there. When I would go to all these candidate kickoffs or these city events, I would just smile every time I saw that he was there because I knew I had someone to talk to and I knew that I would learn something that day. He always shared his perspective and he always got all of us I think from across the aisles

28
00:11:39,989 --> 00:12:07,765
to think bigger and to listen more and to be more empathetic to each other. And that's the kind of man he is. And you see it in the work that he's done even before most of us have met him. That he really is a man of community and someone who really deeply cares. He's someone who always stuck to his guns and

29
00:12:09,368 --> 00:12:37,583
and said, you know, that Medford deserves to be a place where everyone feels welcomed, where everyone gets a say in how things are done. And I could go on and on about LEND, really, because this loss is one of the ones that I think is the toughest for me as a councillor in the city. Through the wake,

30
00:12:38,461 --> 00:13:08,077
I couldn't think for hours just because everything that that has taught me has made me into the person I am today. And I know has made other folks, other politicians, counselors, school committee members in the city, the people that they are today. And his contribution to the city is so immense and it will last for generations. Thank you, Councillor Hussain. Councillor Scarpelli.

31
00:13:10,169 --> 00:13:28,698
1st, let me apologize to the family because, um. This is so important that I wish I was in that seat because that's what Lynn deserves. Um, um, but, um. What everybody said is is boy, did you hit the nail on the head with that?

32
00:13:29,086 --> 00:13:58,853
Being the counselor that's on the other side of a group, you kind of felt alone sometimes. And Len would be that guy that I remembered years ago. I mean, I remember when I started 18 years ago, having that conversation with Len. I think everybody had that conversation with Lenny Gleyoner. And you really wanted to get his blessing because of the type of person he is.

33
00:14:00,457 --> 00:14:21,280
And when everybody talked about him tonight, and you talked about the bridging the gap and trying to find that common denominator that brings everybody together and what's dividing our city. And Len was that bloodline, right? He was really, truly that. There were times that, you know,

34
00:14:22,445 --> 00:14:43,808
privately talked to Len, and I'd want to lambaste him for something, right? What's wrong with you, Len? And he'd sit you down, and with his infinite wisdom, look you right in the eye and tell you how he felt, because he didn't waver in his beliefs. And he brought you over to his side, and he brought me back to the way my dad always taught me, you know, in his Jesuit learning and processing.

35
00:14:43,808 --> 00:14:53,123
in the seminary, my dad always said, always put yourself in the other person's shoes and understand that process. And that's what Len did for me a few times, and I appreciated that.

36
00:14:53,714 --> 00:15:19,735
But really what I find amazing is Lenny Glaiona, the man of Medford and how he raised his family and how he lived his life in Medford. Boy, did he love Medford. And you could see it by what he left to his family. And you can tell how they give back to their community, whether it's coaching or teaching or just being a great neighbor, right?

37
00:15:19,735 --> 00:15:40,829
And, you know, Len was always there. I mean, I still remember my son's first hockey game in the Boston Garden, and it was his birthday. And who do we run into? Lenny in his Boston Garden suit. And I said, yeah, it's John's 10th birthday, Lenny.

38
00:15:40,829 --> 00:15:58,126
look up at the end of the first period, and it was happy birthday, John Scarpelli, and a birthday cake for him. So Len's going to be lost, missed, so God bless you, my friend.

39
00:15:58,632 --> 00:16:21,515
Thank you for what you've given us. And I've said it a thousand times, right? You said, um, you, you lose so many legends, right? Who's going to pick up that torch? And, um, Lenny Gleyona is gone, but his legacy lived forever. Uh, so thank you, my friend. Thank you. Councilor Scarpelli. Councilor Callahan.

40
00:16:24,316 --> 00:16:42,271
Thank you. I just want to chime in with what my fellow counselors have said. Len was truly a unique ability to be a bridge in this city between different people. He really was also such a role model, I think, for everyone involved in politics in any way.

41
00:16:43,857 --> 00:17:09,558
You know, he has left such an incredible and beautiful mark on the city and he will be sorely missed. I think for many years, we will be talking about his presence and what he brought to us. And I'm sad, but he had an incredible, incredible life and I'm very grateful. Thank you. Thank you, Councilor Callahan. Councilor Maloney.

42
00:17:10,098 --> 00:17:38,397
Thank you. There's really not much more I can say than what many of my other counselors have said as well. But personally, as someone who is new to all of this, when I was going through the process, I remember going to an event and everyone was like, you got to talk to Len. If you really want to know what's happening in Medford and really get a sense of what this is, you need to talk to Len. And I remember having my first conversation with him, and he was just so warm.

43
00:17:38,397 --> 00:18:03,338
and welcoming and it felt like there was not any question I could ask that he wouldn't be willing to answer and to be able to help me with. And I still remember when I did my first event and he showed up and it was like, he was like my star person that was at that event. And he was just a wonderful sounding board. And to what everyone has said, he has been an amazing bridge.

44
00:18:03,727 --> 00:18:29,512
I want to thank his family for sharing him with us, and, you know, to thank him for the huge mark that he has left here, and he will be very much missed. Thank you. I think Councilor Mulane, I think Len would want to go seven for seven, and I'm not going to not say something about Len. If we were here in two years, he'd be going 11 for 11.

45
00:18:31,891 --> 00:18:53,440
I'm going to know less about Medford in the next weeks and months because I don't have Len to tell me what's going on. Something that you always knew you were getting when you saw Len was a good story. Most of the time, mostly right. And always shared with good intention.

46
00:18:55,043 --> 00:19:19,613
over the past six and a half years, we've had some rough meetings in this chamber. And going back to my first election, you know, Len didn't meet with me as much because he wanted Nicole to win. And he thought that if I won, maybe Nicole wouldn't. So, but once we both won, Len was like, okay, I'll talk to you. He was nice before that too, but he really wanted Nicole to win.

47
00:19:20,373 --> 00:19:50,225
I'm really glad that he did because my first four years on this body would not have been sustainable or sane without Nicole. And he saw that in Nicole. He knew that she would be an exceptional counselor and chose to support her. And I thought that was, and he was just very passionate about that. But we had some difficult meetings over the years and I'm sure we will have more, although fingers crossed, not for at least a few weeks.

48
00:19:50,765 --> 00:20:08,450
And the one thing that always on the hardest nights really meant a lot was Len would stick around pretty late most of the time or I'd step out for a minute and I'd go to Len and I'd be like, how am I doing? How are we doing? And he'd be like, you're going to be fine.

49
00:20:09,530 --> 00:20:30,607
And when the other 150 people in the room are mad at you, it's nice to know that someone who maybe doesn't even agree with you on the thing that you're fighting about still cared about how you were feeling and wanted to make sure that, you know, wanted to say the right thing at the right time. It really meant a lot to hear that.

50
00:20:32,311 --> 00:20:56,847
I'm going to miss that and I'm going to miss him. And that doesn't even begin to speak to all of the folks in our community who are going to miss him and the way that he showed up for organizations, for city government, for his neighbors, his family, his kids, his grandkids, and for Medford. At the end of the day, Glenn was really for Medford.

51
00:20:58,332 --> 00:21:27,678
I think something that we can all do to honor him is step up for our city. When someone, when you see something, when there's an opportunity to step up for Medford and you're like, I don't know if I'm gonna do it or not, think of Len and say yes. And I think you'll be better off for it and our city will be better off for it too. So with that, we'll go to members of the public and the audience who may like to speak tonight about Len.

52
00:21:30,783 --> 00:21:32,200
Name and address for record, please.

53
00:21:32,268 --> 00:22:01,327
Nicole Morrell, 21 Ronalee Road, former member of this August body. I could, former counselor Penta said it best, so I just have to keep repeating it. And Len would appreciate a call back to old Medford politics. A lot of what I have to say tonight has been said, and as some of you know, I really don't like to repeat other counselors. I like to save the time. But if anyone deserves it, it's Len. So I just want to say a few things about him.

54
00:22:01,327 --> 00:22:25,205
One of the great perks of getting deeply involved in politics in your community are these intergenerational friendships that you otherwise wouldn't have had the opportunity to have. Similar to Vice President Lazaro, I met Len first when I went to my first Medford Democratic Caucus meeting over a decade ago. He quickly clocked me as a new face, and at the time the youngest person there.

55
00:22:25,205 --> 00:22:54,584
and he nominated me to go to the convention, which he went to as well. We reconnected a few years later when I ran for city council, and he quickly became a fixture in my life. Over weekly coffees, a spot on his schedule that I'm pretty sure I usurped from former councilor night, Len regaled me with seven decades of Medford political history and his insights. He offered lots of good advice and the occasional ominous warning from some person you'd never heard of, and I would roll my eyes and he would take it in stride.

56
00:22:54,584 --> 00:23:09,620
He had a genuine nonjudgmental curiosity about politics and people in the city, and he was rewarded for that with friendships of people who have been here forever, who were brand new, people who agreed with him, and people who definitely did not.

57
00:23:10,379 --> 00:23:30,865
Over my political career, Len would rotate through titles for himself within my campaign, senior advisor, old hand, campaign manager. But in retrospect, the most apt title has always been friend. So I'm lucky to call him my friend. The city has been lucky to have him, and we're all going to miss him very much.

58
00:23:30,865 --> 00:23:58,338
And I thank his family for lending him to the city so much, and to every single politician in this room, and everyone who ran or considered running. He was a boon to Medford, and we were lucky to have him. And we're all gonna miss him very much. So thank you for taking the time to have this remembrance on the agenda tonight, and just giving me the time to speak. Appreciate it. Thank you, Madam President.

59
00:24:01,190 --> 00:24:28,544
Is there anyone else who would like to speak at this time to commemorate our friend, Len Galeona? Of course. Thanks for joining us and you can share your name and address to the record. Chris Galeona, 50 Noah Circle. I just want to thank you. This was overwhelming. I appreciate the kind words. Thank you. Thank you. We're sorry for your loss and we'll miss him very much. Is there a motion to approve?

60
00:24:29,810 --> 00:24:57,400
on the motion of Councilor Lemming to approve, seconded by. Seconded by Councilor Callahan. We'll call the roll and then we'll take a moment of silence. Councilor Callahan. Councilor Lemming. Councilor Mullain. Councilor Scarpelli. Yes. Councilor Singh. Yes. Vice President Lazaro. Yes. And President Pierce.

61
